":"Merchant","location":"Stockbridge, Massachusetts","notes":"For a time in business with his brother-in-law William Edwards."},{"role":"Court clerk; State Treasurer","organization":"Hampshire County Court; Commonwealth of Massachusetts"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"career","header":"Harvard man, merchant, and state treasurer","body":"Josiah Dwight graduated from Harvard in 1786 and set up as a merchant at Stockbridge, for a time partnered with his brother-in-law William Edwards. He later served as clerk of the Hampshire County court and as treasurer of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.","number":1},{"category":"family","header":"Rhoda Edwards was his second wife","body":"Dwight first married Caroline Williams in 1789, but she died in 1796. Two years later he married Rhoda Edwards, the celebrated 'Madam Dwight,' with whom he raised fifteen children.","number":2}],"slug":"josiah-dwight-1767"},"H00945":{"id":"H00945","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":6,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"parents":{"father_id":"H00381","mother_id":"X00709"},"tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"EH 1909"}],"birth":{"year":1778,"month":5,"day":7,"city":"Stockbridge","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1863,"month":11,"day":13,"city":"Northampton","county":"Hampshire County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States","age":85},"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00725","children_ids":["HD2281","HD2282","HD2283","HD2284","HD2285","HD2286","HD2287","HD2288","HD2289","HD2290","HD2291","HD2292","HD2293","HD2294","HD2295"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1798,"date_month":3,"date_day":3,"location_city":"Stockbridge","location_state":"Massachusetts"}],"alternate_photo_url":"https://americanaristocracy.com/storage/18324/Screenshot-2024-02-12-at-20.23.36.png","gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Rhoda Edwards","first_name":"Rhoda","maiden_name":"Edwards","married_names":[],"photo_url":"https://res.cloudinary.com/dc5clrqtw/image/upload/v1780756028/Screenshot-2024-02-12-at-20.23.36_qyat8x.png"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Madam Dwight a wonder and joy in Northampton","body":"Contemporary admirers described Rhoda as 'a wonder and a joy to all who knew her, for intellectual power and brightness, to the end of her very long life.' She was held in veneration by the admiring people of Northampton Massachusetts and by 'a multitude without that historic town.' The recognition extended well beyond local family circles into the wider regional culture of mid-nineteenth-century Massachusetts intellectual life."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Mother of fifteen children with Josiah Dwight","body":"Rhoda married Josiah Dwight of Northampton on March 3, 1798 and they had fifteen documented children together. The very large family size placed the Dwight-Edwards household among the more substantial child-bearing marriages of late-eighteenth and early-nineteenth-century western Massachusetts. Josiah died about 1822, leaving Rhoda widowed with many children to raise alone over the next four decades."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Widowed about 1822 with many children","body":"After Josiah's death about 1822, Rhoda raised her surviving children through her long widowhood — she lived another forty-one years until her 1863 death. The decades-long widowhood and intellectual reputation combined to make her one of Northampton's prominent older women of the mid-nineteenth century."},{"number":4,"category":"family","header":"Born Stockbridge MA 1778, died Northampton 1863","body":"Rhoda Edwards was born May 7, 1778 in Stockbridge, Berkshire County Massachusetts and died November 13, 1863 in Northampton, Hampshire County Massachusetts at age eighty-five. She is buried at Bridge Street Cemetery, Northampton. The Stockbridge-to-Northampton life arc tracked her marriage migration about thirty miles east into the Connecticut River valley."}],"slug":"rhoda-edwards-1778"},"X03111":{"id":"X03111","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"male","birth":{"year":1715,"month":10,"day":23,"city":"Hatfield","county":"Hampshire County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1768,"month":9,"day":28,"city":"Springfield","county":"Hampden County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_thomas_spouse":false,"is_talcott_spouse":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_paths_to_thomas":0,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_progenitor":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":["business","law","politics"],"notable_blurb":"Richest man in old Hampshire County","primary_url":"https://americanaristocracy.com/people/col-josiah-dwight","primary_url_label":"American Aristocracy"},"parents":{},"number_of_marriages":2,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X03112","spouse_name":"Sarah Pynchon Dwight","marriage_year":1750,"children_ids":[]},{"spouse_id":"X03113","spouse_name":"Elizabeth Buckminster Dwight","marriage_year":1757,"children_ids":["X00227","X00725"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"business","header":"He ran potash works and an iron foundry","body":"A Yale graduate and Hatfield-born merchant, Josiah Dwight built his fortune at Westfield and Springfield through trade, a potash manufactory, and an iron foundry. He was reckoned the richest man in the old County of Hampshire at his death in 1768.","number":1},{"category":"law","header":"He judged the county court for eighteen years","body":"From 1750 until his death Dwight sat as a judge of the Court of Common Pleas for Hampshire County and held the rank of lieutenant-colonel in the militia. His estate was inventoried at more than nine thousand pounds.","number":2},{"category":"education","header":"A Yale man of the old Dedham Dwights","body":"Dwight graduated from Yale in 1736 and came of the Dedham Dwights, a first cousin of the grandfather of Yale's president Timothy Dwight. He kept shop at Westfield before establishing himself at Springfield.","number":3},{"category":"family","header":"His two daughters married into prominent families","body":"By his second wife, Elizabeth Buckminster, Dwight had five children who lived to maturity. His daughter Sarah married Judge John Hooker, and his son Josiah carried on the Springfield line.","number":4}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[{"landmark_id":"LM120","landmark_blurb":"He built this Springfield house about 1754; it now stands at Historic Deerfield."}],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[{"type":"in_law","related_id":"H00527","display_label":"married his daughter Sarah in 1790"}],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Josiah","last_name":"Dwight","married_names":[],"display_name":"Col. Josiah Dwight","gender":"male"},"military_service":[],"slug":"josiah-dwight-1715"},"X03113":{"id":"X03113","former_ids":[],"is_placeholder":false,"has_descendants_documented":false,"gender":"female","birth":{"year":1730,"month":9,"day":1,"city":"Brookfield","county":"Worcester County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"death":{"year":1798,"month":3,"day":10,"city":"Springfield","county":"Hampden County","state":"Massachusetts","country":"United States"},"classification":{"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"include_in_path_calculation":false,"is_easter_egg":true},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"parents":{"father_name":"Col. Joseph Buckminster of Brookfield"},"number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X03111","spouse_name":"Col. Josiah Dwight","marriage_year":1757,"children_ids":["X00227","X00725"]}],"tags":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"category":"family","header":"Mother of the Springfield Dwight line","body":"Elizabeth Buckminster of Brookfield became Josiah Dwight's second wife in 1757 and bore the five children who survived him. She outlived him by thirty years, dying at Springfield in 1798.","number":1}],"sources":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"research_tags":[],"cross_connections":[],"quotes":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"statues":[],"bio":{"first_name":"Elizabeth","last_name":"Buckminster","married_names":[],"display_name":"Elizabeth Buckminster Dwight","gender":"female"},"military_service":[],"slug":"elizabeth-buckminster-1730"},"H00381":{"id":"H00381","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1738,"month":7,"day":25,"city":"Northampton","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1813},"parents":{"father_id":"X00128","mother_id":"HD0418"},"tags":["lawyer","judge"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 381"}],"prominent_name_reason":"Hon. Timothy Edwards (1738-1813) — Princeton 1757; merchant and judge of Stockbridge MA. His son \"Edward Hooker Edwards\" (b.1763) carried the Hooker name explicitly — a deliberate tribute to the founding ancestor in the 5th generation of Edwards descendants.","marriages":[{"spouse_id":"X00709","children_ids":["H00936","H00937","H00938","H00939","H00940","H00941","H00942","H00943","H00944","H00945","H00946","H00947","H00948","H00949"],"marriage_number":1,"date_year":1760,"date_month":9,"date_day":25,"location_city":"Elizabethtown","location_state":"New Jersey"}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"Governor of NJ 1812"},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Timothy Edwards","first_name":"Timothy","last_name":"Edwards","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"Princeton 1757 — son of Jonathan Edwards","body":"He graduated Princeton in 1757 and went to Elizabethtown, New Jersey to practice law. He moved to Stockbridge, Massachusetts around 1770, where he served as a judge — earning the 'Hon.' style on his name."},{"number":2,"category":"family","header":"Married into the Ogden family of New Jersey","body":"His wife Rhoda Ogden was sister of Aaron Ogden (Governor of New Jersey 1812-1813) and Matthias Ogden, a lieutenant colonel who marched to Quebec with Benedict Arnold in 1775. Through her, the Edwards-Hooker line connected to early New Jersey political and military leadership."},{"number":3,"category":"family","header":"Daughter Phebe married a Hooker — double convergence","body":"His daughter Phebe Edwards married Rev. Asahel Hooker — both descended from Thomas Hooker, creating a double Hooker convergence in their children. Phebe's path back went through her mother Sarah Pierpont Edwards; Asahel's through the main Hartford Hooker line."}],"slug":"timothy-edwards-1738"},"X00709":{"id":"X00709","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1741,"month":9,"day":28,"city":"Elizabethtown","state":"New Jersey"},"dea